            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> Actually, this is a user error. The trailing text column is called t. If you want to address it you use t, e.g.\r\n> \r\n> gmt plot -R0/10/0/10 -BWSne -Baf -JX4c temp.txt -S -i0:2,t -W1p,black -png test\r\n> \r\n> See the [documentation](https://docs.generic-mapping-tools.org/latest/gmt.html#icols-full) for the **-i** option for details.\r\n\r\nThanks! @PaulWessel \r\nI will change the label later. Thank you for your answer!\r\n\r\n\r\nI  am still a bit confused about how the column number is counted.\r\nIt seems we cannot skip one column? Say we have one more column in the middle:\r\n```\r\necho \"5 5 100 0.1c t\" > temp.txt\r\necho \"5 7 100 0.1c c\" > temp.txt\r\n\r\n# This doesn't work \r\ngmt plot -R0/10/0/10 -BWSne -Baf -JX4c temp.txt -S -i0,1,3,t -W1p,black -png test;\r\n```\r\n\r\nAnother case is:\r\n```bash\r\necho \"5 7 0.1c c 100\" > temp.txt\r\n\r\n# We don't need the exact trailing column; and this doesn't work\r\ngmt plot -R0/10/0/10 -BWSne -Baf -JX4c temp.txt -S -i0,1,2,3 -W1p,black -png test;\r\n\r\n# But the one below works\r\ngmt plot -R0/10/0/10 -BWSne -Baf -JX4c temp.txt -S -i0,1,2,t0 -W1p,black -png test;\r\n```\r\n\r\n",
